> At 07:10 PM 2/14/2002, David Bell wrote:
> >Andrew,
> >I also live about 12 miles from town, and I have
> the same model fuel
> guage:
> >reads well when tank is full but after 30 miles it
> reads empty. I am
> waiting
> >to fix it until I have to remove the engine anyway.
> In the mean time, I
> have
> >a post-it note on the dash on which I write down
> the mileage for the next
> >fill-up. To be on the safe side, I fill after 150
> miles (250km?) even
> though
> >I get more miles than that out of a tank of gas.
> 
> Initially I did the same, except I used one of those
> little plastic mileage
> 
> indicators with the moveable dials so you can set it
> to any mileage.  Got
> it at Poop Boys for a few dollars.  You could also
> do what I did later -
> install a Vanagon speedo and use the trip meter. 
> :-)  I can almost
> guarantee you that your sender is bad as my symptoms
> were identical to
> yours.  I've heard that it's possible to swap out
> the sender with the tank
> in place, without cutting through the floor!  If
> you're a contortionist
> maybe?  Not tried it though.  I removed my tank
> while the engine was out
> for a rebuild (and even then it was a dirty, PITA
> job).
> 
> >Just yesterday I filled up
> >after pushing the mileage limits a bit. The book
> says that the tank holds
> >14.8 gallons but the fuel pump registered 14.9! I
> guess I cut that one a
> >little close.
> 
> I've put as much as 15.2 gallons in without running
> out, but I fill it
> until the fuel level is 2" below the cap.  I have to
> put the last 2 gallons
> 
> or so in very slowly.
> 
> 
> >Anyway, just set yourself a reasonable mileage
> range between fill-ups and
> >fix the sender when you have the engine out for
> other work.
> 
> I think that's a great idea!
> 
